. This volume is the product of the Resilience Action Initiative, a collaboration among Dow, DuPont, IBM, McKinsey, Shell, Siemens, Swiss Re, Unilever, and Yara designed to explore possible corporate contributions to global resilience, especially at the nexus of water, food, and energy. Aggressively forward-thinking and consistent with an enlightened self-interest, the ideas considered here represent a corporate perspective on the broad collaborations required for a more resilient world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCorporations. 0aSustainable development. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Corporate & Business History.2bisacsh  aResilience models, water-energy-food nexus.1 aAlbani, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArizzi, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerghuijs, Jaap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoth, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBresch, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBöggemann, Maike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgger, Maximilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgloff, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawkins, Neil C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKupers, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c